post_text: Are you wanting to help support the Spring Hill High School - U.S.D. 230 Debate program this fall? The Debate team is looking for individuals who would be willing to help our students compete by serving as judges. This year, you can judge from anywhere as long as you have internet access, as most of our competitions will be held virtually! If you are interested in helping judge this fall, please fill out the Google Form (https://forms.gle/SkScMbX76zChSddTA) or email Alix Kunkle at kunklea@usd230.org. The Debate team thanks you in advance for your willingness to help and your support!

Spring Hill Human Resources
August 27 at 11:32 AM ¬∑

Please welcome Lucy Mohler to the USD 230 Team! Lucy will be a 2nd and 5th Grade Optional Remote Co-Teacher. Her home base will be at SHES, but she co-teach all of our 2nd and 5th grade ORL students. Lucy is a graduate of KSU and has a great deal of experience delivering instruction in the virtual environment. She believes that giving students ownership over their education and empowering them to take charge of their learning will allow each student to flourish in their own unique way by using their personal skills and abilities in school. Lucy, we are fortunate you have chosen USD 230 as your teaching home! #WhySpringHill

Make your life a masterpiece. Imagine no limitations on what you can be, have or do. -Brian Tracy

Please welcome Meredith Helus to the USD 230 Team! Meredith will be teaching Social Studies at Spring Hill Middle School - U.S.D. 230. She is a graduate of OSU and is currently working on her Masters in Teaching from Avila. Meredith is an innovative educator who enjoys helping students explore what is outside the box. She strives to take material that is considered challenging or boring and find a way to teach it in a way that is simple to understand and enjoyable. Meredith, we are fortunate you have chosen USD 230 as your teaching home! #WhySpringHill

Make each day your masterpiece.-John Wooden

August 26 at 6:50 PM ¬∑

The halls may be empty for Deputy Ramos‚Äô first day at Spring Hill Middle School but he‚Äôs still excited to start his first year as the newest SRO for Spring Hill U.S.D. 230! Deputy Ramos will be joining Deputy Pechnik as our SRO team for the school district. Students may see him popping in on some zoom classes!

We hope everyone had a safe and fun first day of school and we wish all the students, staff, and families a great 2020-2021 school year! We‚Äôre looking forward to walking alongside you as we all adjust and experience this new schooling format!

Zero Reasons Why
July 23 at 9:54 AM ¬∑

Have you registered?! Kyra, #ZeroReasonsWhy Teen Council member from Spring Hill U.S.D. 230, invites you to our quarterly Mental Health Community Convening on Wednesday, July 29 from 4 to 5 p.m., via Zoom Webinar.

As we approach the new school year, we'll focus on how our community can rally around teens during this time, when so many unknowns and questions exist for everyone. Coming together as a united community is more important that ever before, and continued prioritization of teen mental health and suicide prevention should be top of mind. Please join us for this important conversation guided by our teen leaders!

post_text:
Recently, we've had some parents report that emails from the district or their school goes to their Junk/Spam folder. Here are a few ways to make sure you don't miss our emails (depending on the provider):
1) Add the domain @usd230.org to the From field.
2) Add each email as a contact.
3) Check your Junk/Spam folders weekly to make sure emails are being filtered correctly. Mark "Not Spam" if you want that address to filter to your inbox.

post_text: Completing the #2020Census only takes a few minutes and will help your schools, city, county and state!
shared_text:
Miami County, Kansas, Economic Development
June 15 at 4:20 PM ¬∑

1. We are only .1% away from meeting our final 2010 Response Rate. That's just .2% from topping it. If we get there, we would be the first county in the Kansas City Metropolitan Area to beat their 2010 census rate.
2. Spring Hill is back at number 1. Sorry Louisburg.
3. We are doing well, but we are still missing 27.2% of households in Miami County. If we stopped counting today, Miami County could miss out on approximately $182.4 million in federal funding over the next 10 years. That funding is going to be key to a Covid-19 recovery.

post_text: The Spring Hill School District is pleased to announce we will continue to provide meals to children ages 1-18 through June 25, 2020. The first day of summer meals will be Thursday, May 28, 2020 between 11 am - 12:30 pm. We are offering breakfast and lunch for children regardless of income on Mondays and Thursdays (May 28 - June 25). On Monday you will receive meals for Monday, Tuesday and Wednesday. On Thursday you will receive meals for Thursday, Friday and Saturday. To reduce food waste, we request that you register for meals for the upcoming week. The meal form is available on our website and will be available up until midnight the day before a distribution. We will only have two distribution sites during the summer: Spring Hill Elementary School (SHES) and Woodland Spring Middle School (WSMS).

Johnson County, KS Government
April 21 at 12:00 PM ¬∑

Johnson County Department of Health and Environment (JCDHE) is again asking Johnson County residents to complete a short survey in order to help us understand how many people in Johnson County have or do not have symptoms of coronavirus (COVID-19).

This short survey asks about your symptoms or lack of symptoms, demographic and contact information. The survey should be completed for every member of the household. The information is confidential and will only be used by JCDHE to determine how COVID-19 is spreading in the community.

Some residents who complete the survey will be invited to get tested for COVID-19 at a future JCDHE drive-thru testing clinic.

Take the survey at https://jocogov.org/coronavirussurvey

Tonight, Johnson County Government announced that Johnson County public health officer Dr. Joseph LeMaster has signed an order to close all schools in Johnson County through April 5 to help prevent the spread of COVID-19 in our community.

Additional information will be shared in the coming days, including information about educational resources and details related to meals for students in need.

We strongly encourage our families to practice social distancing during this time, to mitigate the spread of this virus. We appreciate your patience as we navigate this challenging and unprecedented situation.

Spring Hill High School - U.S.D. 230
February 11 at 11:34 AM ¬∑

The Forensics team had a strong showing at the Olathe South tournament this weekend, despite facing some stiff competition. Elise Belcher took 9th overall in Original Oration and 8th overall in Impromptu, and Chris Carrel took 14th in Informational. Ally Dickey and Jonah Muro finished 12th and 13th, respectively, in poetry, and Maya Sosa had an excellent Congress session Friday night!

Are YOU interested in learning what Forensics is all about? Come talk to Mr. Kunkle in room 141!
#BroncoPride

Congratulations Chiefs!

Wolf Creek Elementary School
January 23 at 4:27 PM ¬∑

Erica Book is the December Teacher of the Month for Johnson County Pediatric Doctors' Appreciation. Her first grade student, Quintyn Hendrich, put her name in the monthly drawing. She was awarded a $100 gift certificate.

Johnson County Pediatrics started this about a year ago. Every month during the school year, a teacher is awarded. The Pediatric Doctors wanted to show appreciation for teachers and their coordinated efforts to help raise healthy kids.

Congratulations, Erica!
